══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SYSTEM / HEALTH / PROCESSES / SERVER STATUS
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

SERVER-STATUS/SYSTEM-HEALTH/UPTIME/LOAD/TEMPERATURE/MEMORY/DISK
  MUST: get_processes(include_health=true, top=10).
  MUST NOT: call get_processes() without include_health when the user
  asks for a general server/system status/temperature/memory/disk/resources.
  OK: "server status" → get_processes(include_health=true, top=10).
  OK: "cpu temperature" → get_processes(include_health=true).
  OK: "how much ram free" → get_processes(include_health=true).
  OK: "disk space" → get_processes(include_health=true).
  ERROR: "server status" → get_processes(top=10) without include_health.
  ERROR: "cpu temperature" → get_processes() without include_health.
  The `include_health` flag adds load avg + RAM + disks + Metnos services
  + thermal sensors to the result, in ONE single step.

  (health_in_observation_skip) HEALTH BLOCK ALREADY COMPLETE IN OBSERVATION:
      When an executor in history returns an observation with non-empty
      `health` field (load, memory, disk, services) — typical of
      `get_processes(include_health=true)` for queries like "system status",
      "how is the server doing", "load and ram" — the runtime
      AUTOMATICALLY PREPENDS to the final_message a formatted "Server status"
      block (load 1m/5m/15m + uptime, RAM%, disks%, services up/down).
      The user ALREADY SEES the full health data.
    MUST: call `final_answer` directly with a brief comment on processes
         (if relevant) or a closing sentence. Let the "Server status" block
         be the main content.
    MUST NOT: call describe_entries after a get_processes with non-empty
         `health`. describe_entries only sees `entries` (the top processes),
         NOT the `health` field. The LLM will declare "not available" for
         Load/RAM/Disks/Services contradicting the already-present block.
    MUST NOT: re-run `get_processes` or re-ask the status. Data is
         already in history.
    OK: history step1 = get_processes(include_health=true) ok=true,
         entries=[10 processes], health={load,mem,disk,services} →
         step2 final_answer "Status in table above. Top process: python
         33% CPU (nightly orchestrator)".
    OK: same scenario without comment on processes → step2 final_answer
         "Server status above. All nominal.".
    ERROR: same scenario → step2 describe_entries(from_step=1) → the
         LLM says "Load: not available, RAM: not available, ...".
         THIS IS AN ERROR: data is already in the prepended block.
